# Static HTML/JS Site to WordPress Theme Conversion

## Strategy Overview

Convert a single- or multi-page static site into a self-contained WordPress theme where ALL content is editable through wp-admin by a non-technical user. No page builders, no ACF, no premium plugins.

## Step 1: Analyse the Static Site

- Inventory every section/page, noting: headings, text blocks, images, forms, repeating content (staff cards, FAQ items, testimonials, pricing cards).
- Classify each piece of content:
  - **Global text** (hero, about, prices, contact info) → WordPress Customizer settings
  - **Repeating items** (staff, FAQ, portfolio, testimonials) → Custom Post Types (CPTs)
  - **Forms** (contact, booking) → Contact Form 7 plugin with HTML fallback
  - **Navigation** → `register_nav_menus()` + custom Walker if needed
  - **Static assets** (images, fonts, JS) → `assets/` subfolder inside theme

## Step 2: Scaffold the Theme

Required file structure:

```
theme-name/
├── style.css              # Must start with WP theme header comment
├── functions.php          # Setup, enqueues, walker, helpers
├── index.php              # REQUIRED fallback template
├── front-page.php         # Static front page template (if one-page)
├── header.php             # <head>, nav
├── footer.php             # Footer, wp_footer()
├── assets/
│   ├── js/                # Copy original JS here
│   └── images/            # Copy ALL original images here
├── inc/
│   ├── customizer.php     # Customizer panels, sections, settings, controls
│   ├── post-types.php     # CPT registrations + meta boxes
│   └── theme-setup.php    # Theme activation hook: seed pages, menus, CPTs, CF7
└── template-parts/
    └── section-*.php      # One file per page section
```

### Critical: index.php is REQUIRED

WordPress will refuse to install a theme without `index.php`. Even if `front-page.php` handles the homepage, `index.php` must exist as a fallback. Copy the same include logic from `front-page.php`.

### Critical: style.css Header

```css
/*
Theme Name: My Theme
Theme URI: https://example.com/
Author: Author Name
Version: 1.0.0
Requires at least: 6.0
Requires PHP: 7.4
Text Domain: my-theme
*/
```

The `Text Domain` must match the folder name and be used in ALL translation functions.

## Step 3: functions.php Patterns

```php
// 1. Constants
define( 'THEME_VERSION', '1.0.0' );

// 2. Theme setup (after_setup_theme)
// - add_theme_support: title-tag, post-thumbnails, custom-logo, html5
// - register_nav_menus

// 3. Enqueue assets (wp_enqueue_scripts)
// - Google Fonts, icon libraries via wp_enqueue_style
// - Theme style.css via get_stylesheet_uri()
// - Theme JS via wp_enqueue_script with jquery dependency, in footer

// 4. Include files
require_once get_template_directory() . '/inc/post-types.php';
require_once get_template_directory() . '/inc/customizer.php';
require_once get_template_directory() . '/inc/theme-setup.php';

// 5. Custom nav walker (if original nav needs specific classes)
// 6. Helper function: theme_get_option() wrapper around get_theme_mod()
```

### CRITICAL: No Duplicate Functions

Never define the same function in multiple files. If a helper like `get_option()` is in `functions.php`, do NOT also define it in `customizer.php` or elsewhere. **Duplicate function definitions cause fatal errors.**

## Step 4: Customizer Settings

For each text block on the static site:

```php
$wp_customize->add_setting( 'prefix_setting_key', array(
    'default'           => 'Original static text here',
    'sanitize_callback' => 'sanitize_text_field', // or wp_kses_post for HTML
) );
$wp_customize->add_control( 'prefix_setting_key', array(
    'label'   => __( 'Human label', 'text-domain' ),
    'section' => 'prefix_section',
    'type'    => 'textarea', // or 'text', 'url', 'email'
) );
```

- Pre-populate ALL defaults with the original static text so the site looks identical on first activation.
- Use `sanitize_text_field` for plain text, `wp_kses_post` for HTML, `esc_url_raw` for URLs.

### Make EVERYTHING Editable

- **Every visible text** must be a Customizer setting — section labels, headings, paragraphs, button texts, badge texts, notes, copyright, etc. Zero `esc_html_e()` calls in templates; all text comes from `lo_get_option()` with defaults.
- **Section headers**: each section should have at minimum a `_label` (small text above heading) and `_title` (h2 heading) setting.
- **Comma-separated lists** (e.g. insurance companies) are OK for simple lists, but for items with icons, use individual fields per item instead.

### Icon Fields as Dropdowns

For every element that displays a Font Awesome icon, add a paired icon Customizer setting:

```php
// Define a helper function returning all available icons
function my_get_icon_choices() {
    return array(
        ''             => '— Ingen ikon —',
        'fa-heart'     => 'Hjerte (fa-heart)',
        'fa-user-md'   => 'Lege (fa-user-md)',
        // ... 150+ icons organized by category with human-readable labels
    );
}

// Use 'select' type with choices instead of 'text'
$wp_customize->add_setting( 'prefix_icon', array( 'default' => 'fa-heart', 'sanitize_callback' => 'sanitize_text_field' ) );
$wp_customize->add_control( 'prefix_icon', array( 'label' => 'Ikon', 'section' => '...', 'type' => 'select', 'choices' => my_get_icon_choices() ) );
```

- Include ALL icons from the original static site in the choices array.
- Add many extras from the same icon library, organized by category (healthcare, business, navigation, etc.).
- Use the same helper function for both Customizer controls and CPT meta box dropdowns.
- The "— Ingen ikon —" (empty string) option lets users remove an icon entirely.

## Step 5: Custom Post Types

For repeating content (staff, FAQ, testimonials, **and content cards like treatments**):

```php
add_action( 'init', 'register_my_cpts' );
function register_my_cpts() {
    register_post_type( 'staff', array(
        'labels'        => array( /* Norwegian or English labels */ ),
        'public'        => true,
        'show_in_rest'  => true,
        'supports'      => array( 'title', 'editor', 'thumbnail', 'page-attributes' ),
        'menu_icon'     => 'dashicons-businessperson',
        'has_archive'   => false,
    ) );
}
```

- Use `page-attributes` support for sort order via `menu_order`.
- Add meta boxes for extra fields (professional title, education, etc.) with nonce verification.
- **Do NOT use PHP return type declarations** (`: void`, `: int`) or scalar type hints (`int $id`) for maximum hosting compatibility.

### CPT Meta Box Icon Dropdowns

When a CPT has an icon field (e.g. treatment card icon), use a `<select>` dropdown in the meta box instead of a text input:

```php
function render_icon_meta_box( $post ) {
    wp_nonce_field( 'save_icon', 'icon_nonce' );
    $icon = get_post_meta( $post->ID, '_my_icon', true );
    $choices = function_exists( 'my_get_icon_choices' ) ? my_get_icon_choices() : array();
    echo '<select name="_my_icon" style="width:100%">';
    foreach ( $choices as $value => $label ) {
        printf( '<option value="%s"%s>%s</option>', esc_attr( $value ), selected( $icon, $value, false ), esc_html( $label ) );
    }
    echo '</select>';
}
```

This reuses the same icon choices helper function as the Customizer, giving users a consistent icon selection experience across CPTs and Customizer settings.

### When to Use CPTs vs Customizer for Content Cards

- **Use CPTs** when items are naturally repeatable (variable count) and share a structure (title + content + icon + order). Users add/delete entries in wp-admin → Custom Post Type menu. Examples: treatments, staff, FAQ items.
- **Use Customizer** when items are fixed in number (e.g. exactly 3 hero badges, exactly 6 process steps) and unlikely to grow. Each gets its own settings for text + icon.

## Step 6: Template Parts

Convert each static HTML section into `template-parts/section-name.php`:

```php
<?php if ( ! defined( 'ABSPATH' ) ) exit; ?>
<?php $text = theme_get_option( 'prefix_key', 'Default text' ); ?>

<section class="original-class" id="original-id">
    <div class="container">
        <h2><?php echo esc_html( $text ); ?></h2>
    </div>
</section>
```

- Preserve ALL original CSS classes and IDs exactly.
- Use `esc_html()` for text output, `esc_url()` for URLs, `esc_attr()` for attributes, `wp_kses_post()` for rich HTML.
- For CPT sections, use `WP_Query` with `wp_reset_postdata()` after the loop.

### Conditional Rendering (Hide-When-Empty)

**Every** configurable element must be wrapped in a conditional check so that if the text content is empty, the entire element (including its icon) is hidden:

```php
<?php
$text = lo_get_option( 'prefix_card_text', 'Default' );
$icon = lo_get_option( 'prefix_card_icon', 'fa-heart' );
if ( ! empty( trim( $text ) ) ) : ?>
    <div class="card">
        <?php if ( ! empty( $icon ) ) : ?>
            <i class="fas <?php echo esc_attr( $icon ); ?>"></i>
        <?php endif; ?>
        <span><?php echo esc_html( $text ); ?></span>
    </div>
<?php endif; ?>
```

- The outer `if` checks the **text** (the primary content). If text is empty, the entire block including the icon is hidden.
- The inner `if` checks the **icon**. If the icon dropdown is set to "— Ingen ikon —" (empty string) but text is present, the icon alone is hidden while the text still renders.
- This pattern applies to badges, cards, process steps, benefit items, stats, CTA buttons — everything configurable.

### CSS Grid Auto-Reflow

When elements can be hidden dynamically, use `auto-fit` grids so the layout reorganizes automatically:

```css
.cards-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 2rem;
}
```

- **Never** use a fixed column count (e.g. `repeat(3, 1fr)`) for grids with conditionally rendered items.
- Use `auto-fit` with `minmax(Xpx, 1fr)` where X is the minimum card width.
- This ensures that hiding 1 of 3 cards makes the remaining 2 expand, hiding 2 of 3 makes the last one full-width, etc.
- Apply the same pattern in responsive media queries.

## Step 7: Theme Activation Setup

Hook into `after_switch_theme` to auto-populate:
- Create a front page and set Settings > Reading to static page
- Create the nav menu with all section anchors
- Create initial CPT posts with full content from the static site
- Create CF7 form if plugin is active (with defensive checks)

All creation must be **idempotent** — check for existing content before creating.

## Step 8: Contact Form

- Use Contact Form 7 plugin for form handling.
- In the template, check for CF7 with `shortcode_exists('contact-form-7')`.
- Include a static HTML fallback form (e.g. FormSubmit.co) if CF7 is not installed.

## Step 9: Nav Walker (if needed)

If the original site uses specific CSS classes on nav items:

```php
// Use a filter to flag special items BEFORE the walker runs
add_filter( 'wp_nav_menu_objects', 'flag_last_item', 10, 2 );

// Then check $item->classes in the walker's start_el()
```

**Do NOT** try to access `$args->menu` inside the walker's `start_el()` — it is an empty string at that point. Use a `wp_nav_menu_objects` filter instead.

## Step 10: Packaging & Deployment

```powershell
Compress-Archive -Path "theme-folder" -DestinationPath "theme-folder.zip"
```

Upload via wp-admin: Utseende → Temaer → Legg til ny → Last opp tema.

### Naming Conflicts

If a theme with the same folder name already exists on the server, WordPress will show a conflict. Use a unique folder name (e.g. append `-v2`). Update ALL references: folder name, style.css `Text Domain`, all translation function calls, deploy scripts, and documentation.

## Checklist Before Deployment

- [ ] `index.php` exists (WordPress refuses install without it)
- [ ] `style.css` has valid theme header with `Text Domain` matching folder name
- [ ] No duplicate function definitions across files
- [ ] No PHP return type declarations (`: void`) for hosting compatibility
- [ ] All Customizer defaults populated with original content
- [ ] All images copied to `assets/images/`
- [ ] `wp_head()` in header, `wp_footer()` before `</body>`
- [ ] All output escaped (`esc_html`, `esc_attr`, `esc_url`, `wp_kses_post`)
- [ ] CF7 integration has fallback and defensive null checks
- [ ] Theme activation hook is idempotent
- [ ] ZIP structure: `theme-name/style.css` (one level of nesting)
- [ ] **Every** visible text is a Customizer setting — no hardcoded strings in templates
- [ ] **Every** icon is a Customizer dropdown or CPT meta box dropdown
- [ ] Icon helper function is defined in ONE place (`functions.php`) and reused everywhere
- [ ] Conditional rendering: empty text hides entire element including icon
- [ ] CSS grids use `auto-fit` + `minmax` for layouts with conditionally rendered items
- [ ] CPTs for repeating content are seeded on theme activation with original site data
- [ ] User guide (BRUKERVEILEDNING.md) covers all Customizer settings and CPT editing
